Cell[CellGroupData[{

Cell["Robotic Applications of Prehensile Tails", "Subsection",
 CellChangeTimes->{{3.99254910817247*^9, 
  3.992549119221702*^9}},ExpressionUUID->"7ab70ed5-5376-44e4-8751-\
d9548e566cf7"],

Cell[TextData[{
 "This unique adaptation of a prehensile tail is distinctly missing in humans \
due to their evolved bipedal nature.  In cases of poor footing, balancing \
becomes a challenges. In such cases, not having a tail is a disadvantage. To \
address this problem, prehensile tails have been studied extensively in \
robotics. To make smaller, jumping robots stable, researchers have developed \
a PD controller that naturally adjusts to midair perturbations by modeling a ",
 StyleBox["Velociraptor mongoliensis\[CloseCurlyQuote]",
  FontSlant->"Italic"],
 " tail behaviors (Libby et al., 2012). More accurately to the goals of my \
project, researchers have also ran simulations on the effects of tails on \
inducing rotational forces on 3D objects. By removing all environmental \
forces and then moving a single-jointed tail, they found that the whole \
object moved as a result (Fu et al., 2024). "
}], "Text",
 CellChangeTimes->{{3.992549122381385*^9, 3.992549122700102*^9}, {
   3.992552256920341*^9, 3.992552272457966*^9}, 3.9925525902701*^9, {
   3.992552644865222*^9, 3.99255268359146*^9}, {3.992552786326446*^9, 
   3.992552864535665*^9}, {3.992552994154414*^9, 3.992553047371229*^9}, {
   3.992553206978046*^9, 3.99255324614108*^9}, {3.992553299994673*^9, 
   3.9925533188577547`*^9}, {3.992553365082779*^9, 3.992553467981078*^9}, {
   3.992556419347168*^9, 3.99255646615014*^9}, {3.9925986582957363`*^9, 
   3.992598680301491*^9}, {3.99260047603397*^9, 3.9926006740352173`*^9}, {
   3.992600715032551*^9, 
   3.9926008465381947`*^9}},ExpressionUUID->"dd9522e2-1512-4dfb-98a6-\
a8afcd823a67"],

Cell["\<\
To directly address the balance issue listed above, researchers in Japan \
developed Arque, a robotic tail with pneumatic-based motion for joints, which \
automatically balances a leaning mass through positioning joints in an \
equilibrium state (Junichi Nabeshima et al., 2019). \
\>", "Text",
 CellChangeTimes->{{3.992549122381385*^9, 3.992549122700102*^9}, {
   3.992552256920341*^9, 3.992552272457966*^9}, 3.9925525902701*^9, {
   3.992552644865222*^9, 3.99255268359146*^9}, {3.992552786326446*^9, 
   3.992552864535665*^9}, {3.992552994154414*^9, 3.992553047371229*^9}, {
   3.992553206978046*^9, 3.99255324614108*^9}, {3.992553299994673*^9, 
   3.9925533188577547`*^9}, {3.992553365082779*^9, 3.992553467981078*^9}, {
   3.992556419347168*^9, 3.99255646615014*^9}, {3.9925986582957363`*^9, 
   3.992598680301491*^9}, {3.99260047603397*^9, 3.9926006740352173`*^9}, {
   3.992600715032551*^9, 
   3.992600839809454*^9}},ExpressionUUID->"e72ff72a-0f49-e948-9fcb-\
afa7edac9a3a"]
}, Open  ]],

Cell[CellGroupData[{

Cell["Objectives", "Subsection",
 CellChangeTimes->{{3.9925492475048103`*^9, 
  3.992549248589406*^9}},ExpressionUUID->"7b033e02-4fae-4380-a00e-\
ff18c1f343a5"],

Cell[TextData[{
 "From the above context, it can be concluded that robotic tails currently \
are meant to stabilize and balance. However, each has vastly different \
parameters, lengths, specifications, and masses. In general, some of the most \
complex and cutting-edge robotics research surrounding this topic comes from \
Arque and analysis of simian/primate tails. To assist in this process and \
development, I researched and created an algorithm using advanced \
computation, physics, and biomechanics that aim to answer the question: ",
 StyleBox["C",
  FontWeight->"Bold"],
 StyleBox["an a model be developed with any mass, length, and joint \
parameters where a prehensile tail still balances a mass?",
  FontWeight->"Bold"]
}], "Text",
 CellChangeTimes->{{3.992549249801353*^9, 3.992549249976491*^9}, {
  3.992553473043214*^9, 3.992553488175907*^9}, {3.9925537342873096`*^9, 
  3.9925539345506372`*^9}, {3.992598905525834*^9, 3.9925989430462923`*^9}, {
  3.9926008683626614`*^9, 
  3.99260092346084*^9}},ExpressionUUID->"360f7724-b6b8-4b94-a718-\
8eb394a952cf"]
}, Open  ]]
}, Open  ]],

Cell[CellGroupData[{

Cell["Methodology", "Section",
 CellChangeTimes->{{3.929354612578005*^9, 3.929354616192994*^9}, {
  3.929355210549653*^9, 3.9293552190879917`*^9}, {3.9918429510719347`*^9, 
  3.991842958992612*^9}, {3.992549126790882*^9, 
  3.992549129253162*^9}},ExpressionUUID->"8ec9e2ca-5a23-4872-94fa-\
8fb6c37b3785"],

Cell[CellGroupData[{

Cell["Model V1 - Self-Balancing Tail with Variable Length", "Subsection",
 CellChangeTimes->{{3.9925491382369013`*^9, 
  3.992549139281831*^9}},ExpressionUUID->"c2cac425-9e21-4c1d-bfc1-\
7b637835e0d5"],

Cell["\<\
I started by developing a very simple model. Before changing the angle of the \
tail or adding more joints, I defined how balance works. In physics, balance \
is achieved by having a net torque of zero in the system. In this case, the \
system is defined as the following: a center of mass for the tail offset by a \
distance and a center of mass for the head offset by a distance and height. \
The tail\[CloseCurlyQuote]s center of mass is the midpoint because it is a \
normal object while the head is a point mass. For all calculations, SI units \
were used.\
\>", "Text",
 CellChangeTimes->{{3.9293546184036617`*^9, 3.9293546199188967`*^9}, {
   3.991843023893482*^9, 3.991843098671399*^9}, {3.991843141651308*^9, 
